Of note - before the trees started dying about 5 years ago we assumed that this site was a perfect place for cedar. Also of note, when a tree dies it often does so very quickly - within a few months from healthy looking to dead.

column16:
I live in a HOA that has a greenbelt of about two hundred acres. Cedars that were large and healthy have been dying. We removed about eighty trees last year that suddenly died and we removed seventy more this year. This year the dead tree list also had hemlocks. I think we will lose all of our hemlocks soon and many, many of our cedars have thin tops, dead tops, or just up and died. The dead trees are of all sizes from a yard or more in diameter to ten inches. The die off started in the more moist areas of the greenbelt but is spreading. 
The greenbelt is in what is essentially a housing development but there are rules to protect trees. The ground varies from dry to wet. There are areas that probably should never have been platted due to wetness.  The ground has a gradual slope.

Majority of cedars in the immediate area are of similar size and condition (thin canopy/dead branches at the bottoms, full canopy at the top). Over 10 in similar condition nearby.
